{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5368","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:16:00 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:16:00 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">The suffix <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> has two essential functions:<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">1. It denotes prototypically the <strong>grammatical patient<\/strong> of the verbal action in the perfective past. That is, it refers to the direct object when it is used with a transitive verb or the subject when it is used with an intransitive verb. (From a syntactic point of view, the nominalized verb functions here as a head noun or as a modifier of the head noun.)<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">Constructions using this nominalizer may be translated in English by using a relative clause or a past participle:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f5f\u0f7c\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cThat which has been built\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0fb2\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cThat which has been written\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f40\u0fb2\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cThat which has been washed\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f66\u0fa1\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> \u201c(The person) who lived, sat\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f61\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> \u201c(The person) who came\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f44\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> \u201c(The person) who cried\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f49\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> \u201c(The person) who went to bed\u201d <\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">However, it also extends to the subject of transitive benefactive verbs:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f61\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> \u201c(The person) who has\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f50\u0f7c\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> \u201c(The person) who has obtained\u201d<\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">2. The suffix <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> may also be neutral and nominalize the <strong>entire clause<\/strong>.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">In this case, the suffix is not oriented toward any grammatical role and nominalizes the entire clause. From a syntactic point of view, the nominalized verb functions as a head noun and may be translated in English by a verb in the infinitive, an -<em>ing <\/em>clause, a <em>that <\/em>clause, or even by a noun.<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f68\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f50\u0f7c\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f62\u0f0b\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f42\u0f60\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cThe fact that she took first place made me happy.\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f90\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f64\u0f7a\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f7a\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cIt\u2019s very important to know Tibetan.\u201d Or, \u201cKnowledge of Tibetan is very important.\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f42\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f90\u0fb2\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f5b\u0f74\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f50\u0f74\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f54\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cTo be able to plant hair on the head is incredible!\u201d<\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">It is only from the context that we can distinguish between the two functions described above, as the following examples show:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f72\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f74\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cWho\u2019s the person who came a short while ago?\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f72\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f51\u0f72\u0f62\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f5e\u0f42<\/span> \u201cIt was a good thing \/ idea (for us) to come here today!\u201d<\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">What is being nominalized in the first case is the verb \u201cto come\u201d modifying the head noun \u201cthis one\u201d; in the second, the clause \u201cwe came here today\u201d is being nominalized.<\/p>","title":""}]}
